Rym: You're going to wonder why I keep talking about so much metamoment.

399
00:26:51,680 --> 00:26:54,260
Rym: I'm like, yeah, let's get into it then.

400
00:26:54,541 --> 00:26:58,940
Rym: So we played this game at RevuCon called Space Cube.

401
00:26:59,481 --> 00:27:07,460
Rym: So this game is called Sidereal Confluence, Trading and Negotiation in the Elysian Quadrant.

402
00:27:07,600 --> 00:27:18,660
Scott: Now, the story that was told to me about this game, I don't know if it's true or not, but I totally believe it is that someone was trying to make a big four or five X game like, you know, Master of Orion Eclipse situation.

403
00:27:19,564 --> 00:27:21,260
Scott: And they ended up making so much game.

404
00:27:21,682 --> 00:27:29,300
Scott: But then in the revision phase, they wisely trimmed away because that's what makes things good is remove all and remove all the cruft.

405
00:27:29,400 --> 00:27:31,120
Scott: And so you get the pure magical essence.

406
00:27:31,623 --> 00:27:49,240
Scott: And apparently they removed everything from the game, the combat, everything except for this one part of the game where you deal with space trading of cubes and machines and stuff and this free trading mechanic and removed all the other parts of the game.

407
00:27:49,521 --> 00:27:55,560
Rym: So on the super, super high level, everyone has a unique asymmetric character with its own nonsense.

408
00:27:55,780 --> 00:27:55,881
Scott: Right.

409
00:27:55,901 --> 00:28:01,420
Scott: So I got handed this big old card that looked like a race from like, you know, a game like Master of Orion.

410
00:28:01,641 --> 00:28:05,867
Scott: And I'm like reading all this text and I'm like, oh, my God, why do I have to play this?

411
00:28:05,948 --> 00:28:08,020
Scott: I don't want to let this be a video game.

412
00:28:08,140 --> 00:28:10,159
Scott: I don't want to learn all this while you're reading it.

413
00:28:10,260 --> 00:28:11,300
Rym: So I flip mine over.

414
00:28:11,680 --> 00:28:18,903
Rym: And what I saw on the other side actually terrified me because there was way more shit back there and it looked like game mechanics.

415
00:28:19,144 --> 00:28:23,020
Scott: Yeah, but I'm reading this card and I'm like, why these stupid nerds?

416
00:28:23,480 --> 00:28:24,940
Scott: I can't play nerdy games like this anymore.

417
00:28:25,181 --> 00:28:25,760
Scott: I'm not in high school.

418
00:28:25,981 --> 00:28:29,739
Rym: The thing I see is that the game starts getting unpacked, all these cards start coming out.

419
00:28:30,160 --> 00:28:33,820
Scott: There's like a million cards with a million symbols and a pile of cubes.

420
00:28:33,940 --> 00:28:35,018
Scott: And I'm like, oh, my God.

421
00:28:35,360 --> 00:28:40,000
Rym: And the fascinating thing about this game and before we move any further, it wasn't bad.

422
00:28:40,021 --> 00:28:40,719
Rym: I had a good time with it.

423
00:28:40,840 --> 00:28:42,680
Rym: Like, don't think that we're about to say this game is bad.

424
00:28:43,120 --> 00:28:46,180
Scott: No, I'm just telling you what I was feeling at the time as a chronology.

425
00:28:46,421 --> 00:28:48,379
Rym: But when I looked at the cards.

426
00:28:49,923 --> 00:28:51,980
Rym: It looked like ridiculous bullshit.

427
00:28:52,680 --> 00:28:58,100
Scott: The graphic design has much to be desired and it makes it look like a scary game.

428
00:28:58,220 --> 00:29:03,060
Rym: And like the thing is, it is a scary game, but not nearly as scary as it appears to be.

429
00:29:03,280 --> 00:29:04,579
Scott: No, that's the thing I'm trying to get at.

430
00:29:04,660 --> 00:29:08,960
Scott: is the game looks way scarier than it really is.

431
00:29:09,521 --> 00:29:26,539
Scott: If it had a graphic design makeover and shrunk those alien race cards to be a bit smaller because they don't need to be that big and remove some of its heritage of being a space game, that was about four X or whatever, you would actually be able to see what this game is.

432
00:29:26,801 --> 00:29:29,300
Scott: You know, you can't judge this game by the cover, right?

433
00:29:29,744 --> 00:29:34,740
Scott: If you made it so you could judge it by the cover, then all those feelings from the start of it would go away.

434
00:29:34,882 --> 00:29:39,320
Scott: And you just have the reality of it, which is it's a lot like just a free trading game.

435
00:29:39,740 --> 00:29:42,738
Scott: You trade stuff for stuff and see who gets the most victory points at the end.

436
00:29:43,181 --> 00:29:43,585
Scott: That's it.

437
00:29:43,928 --> 00:29:45,219
Scott: That's really all there is to it.

438
00:29:45,541 --> 00:29:57,124
Rym: So thus the very fascinating things about this game was that once we learn the core mechanics, which took a while, I'm very much reminded of the concept of naive art.

439
00:29:57,485 --> 00:30:03,699
Rym: when there is a known craft with its own sort of assumptions and best practices like knitting or whatever.

440
00:30:04,345 --> 00:30:25,779
Rym: So it is entirely possible for someone who has never studied knitting, never read a knitting book, but has simply enjoyed the knitting of others and just started on their own learning how to knit, they might make perfectly great things, but they might do things in ways that would seem weird to someone who has more like domain knowledge of the craft.

441
00:30:26,142 --> 00:30:29,100
Scott: Yeah, because they don't know they're not learning from the past.

442
00:30:29,200 --> 00:30:33,259
Scott: They're just trying to learn on their own and rediscovering everything that has already been learned.

443
00:30:33,884 --> 00:30:42,680
Rym: And I don't know if that's what happened with this game, but quote naive art is any form of visual art that is created by a person who lacks the formal education and training the professional undergoes, blah, blah, blah.

444
00:30:42,900 --> 00:30:45,078
Scott: But it feels like that's what this game is.

445
00:30:45,460 --> 00:30:56,240
Rym: In the sense that the mechanics it has are not that far from mechanics that I am well used to in just my general board gaming experience.

446
00:30:56,622 --> 00:31:00,460
Rym: And anyone who plays euro games has encountered time and time again.

447
00:31:00,942 --> 00:31:11,780
Rym: But the way they are presented, the way they are explained, the proper nouns, all those things made them alien to me until it was explained.

448
00:31:12,561 --> 00:31:21,979
Rym: The things are not called what I expect them to be called mechanics that I would expect to be explained simply or explained in great depth, but end up being the simple mechanic I didn't expect them to be.

449
00:31:22,460 --> 00:31:23,298
Rym: Things like that.

450
00:31:24,301 --> 00:31:34,960
Rym: The other fascinating thing is that this game, the individual cards, like the player boards, give very specific advice on how you should play that character.

451
00:31:35,442 --> 00:31:37,220
Scott: And it was very not right advice.

452
00:31:37,420 --> 00:31:45,380
Rym: Well, mine was actually pretty much extremely right, because all mine said was you're going to have this one machine out fucking use it as much as possible.

453
00:31:45,560 --> 00:31:45,864
Scott: Oh, OK.

454
00:31:45,884 --> 00:31:47,140
Scott: That's an advice you could actually follow.

455
00:31:47,280 --> 00:31:47,943
Rym: So you know what I did?

456
00:31:48,587 --> 00:31:56,040
Rym: I did nothing but get the cubes to fuel that machine and make sure that I fueled it every single round, no matter what.

457
00:31:56,360 --> 00:31:58,260
Scott: So basically, so here's how the game works.

458
00:31:58,381 --> 00:31:58,623
Scott: Right.

459
00:31:58,744 --> 00:32:04,300
Scott: Is you basically have these cards and each card is a machine and it has a cube that goes in and cubes that come out.

460
00:32:04,380 --> 00:32:07,919
Scott: So you have a. I'm just going to make up a machine off my head because I can't see any right now.

461
00:32:08,080 --> 00:32:14,400
Scott: I'm looking for one blue cube comes in and purple cube and a victory point come out.

462
00:32:14,461 --> 00:32:15,619
Scott: That's actually a way good machine.

463
00:32:15,901 --> 00:32:18,380
Scott: It's like, you know, this victory point is rare.

464
00:32:18,600 --> 00:32:18,682
Rym: Yeah.

465
00:32:18,702 --> 00:32:19,758
Scott: Victory point is super rare.

466
00:32:20,281 --> 00:32:26,380
Scott: There's big cubes which are medium rare, small cubes, which are super common, you know, and you have all these machines in front of you.

467
00:32:26,742 --> 00:32:30,560
Scott: And what you'd really like to do is use every machine, every turn.

468
00:32:30,800 --> 00:32:35,400
Rym: That would be ideal because every machine outputs more than you put into it.

469
00:32:35,500 --> 00:32:35,681
Scott: Yeah.

470
00:32:35,702 --> 00:32:38,359
Scott: There's no machine that is not beneficial to run.

471
00:32:39,001 --> 00:32:39,283
Scott: Right.

472
00:32:39,544 --> 00:32:44,639
Scott: So you want to run every machine you can to basically increase your economy, get more stuff.

473
00:32:45,103 --> 00:32:46,779
Scott: If you have more stuff, you can do more stuff.

474
00:32:47,100 --> 00:32:49,159
Scott: If you can do more stuff, you can get more victory points and win.

475
00:32:49,626 --> 00:32:49,891
Scott: All right.

476
00:32:50,055 --> 00:32:50,259
Scott: Yeah.

477
00:32:50,500 --> 00:32:55,743
Scott: Also, every round you're going to produce a bunch of cubes from these planets you have.

478
00:32:55,945 --> 00:32:57,600
Scott: They just spit out cubes for nothing.

479
00:32:58,661 --> 00:33:01,600
Scott: Also, every round is the sequence where you can.

480
00:33:01,880 --> 00:33:04,079
Rym: I think I had some planets that I actually had to put a cube on.

481
00:33:04,581 --> 00:33:04,788
Scott: Really?

482
00:33:04,892 --> 00:33:05,100
Scott: I didn't.

483
00:33:05,804 --> 00:33:07,420
Scott: Uh, anyway, I think I did anyway.

484
00:33:07,640 --> 00:33:09,540
Rym: I kind of remember this game was so I got to look at my phone.

485
00:33:09,660 --> 00:33:10,799
Rym: I took pictures of my board.

486
00:33:11,020 --> 00:33:18,660
Scott: Anyway, there's also a phase everywhere where you secretly do a simultaneous reveal of stuff to try to win new planets with ships or something.

487
00:33:18,940 --> 00:33:19,061
Rym: Yeah.

488
00:33:19,121 --> 00:33:21,779
Rym: There was a moderate amount of drama there that I actually did enjoy, too.

489
00:33:21,966 --> 00:33:22,178
Rym: Yeah.

490
00:33:23,341 --> 00:33:31,120
Scott: But in the end, it's the main part of the game is there is a phase in which you freely trade stuff with everybody.

491
00:33:31,504 --> 00:33:33,140
Scott: You can make deals for the future.

492
00:33:33,461 --> 00:33:37,500
Scott: You can do a completely free trading, even more than traders of Genoa.

493
00:33:37,781 --> 00:33:41,660
Scott: You can just trade whatever you can feel like multiplayer trades.

494
00:33:41,781 --> 00:33:43,740
Rym: Like, yeah, I'll give you four cubes.

495
00:33:43,780 --> 00:33:47,700
Rym: You can let each of you give me one of these cubes and then you can trade planets.

496
00:33:47,860 --> 00:33:50,859
Scott: You can lend someone a machine for a turn that you then get back.

497
00:33:51,041 --> 00:33:54,700
Scott: You can there's a one character as wild cubes that no one else has.

498
00:33:54,780 --> 00:33:55,959
Scott: They can trade those.

499
00:33:56,462 --> 00:33:58,039
Scott: It's like you can trade your ships.

500
00:33:58,260 --> 00:34:00,959
Rym: What's funny is no one wanted his wild cubes like no one needed them.

501
00:34:01,100 --> 00:34:04,080
Scott: You can trade friggin anything for anything.

502
00:34:04,100 --> 00:34:09,938
Scott: So you basically what you do is you assign all the cubes you have to your machines to say, aha, this is how many machines I can run.

503
00:34:10,322 --> 00:34:12,400
Scott: Then you look and you say, well, I could run that machine.

504
00:34:12,480 --> 00:34:18,420
Scott: If I had one more blue cube, you look at the cubes you're not using and you say, hey, who wants to trade me a blue cube for these cubes?

505
00:34:18,501 --> 00:34:20,599
Scott: I'm not using and maybe someone else has a blue cube.

506
00:34:20,679 --> 00:34:21,385
Scott: They're not using.

507
00:34:21,728 --> 00:34:26,078
Scott: And now both of you end up running more machines if you make the trade and so on.

508
00:34:28,042 --> 00:34:31,600
Scott: So every turn you're trying to make trades to run as many machines as you can.

509
00:34:31,699 --> 00:34:34,580
Scott: And then you try to get stuff in the auctions and the buying phases.

510
00:34:34,920 --> 00:34:44,440
Rym: So what you're actually trying to get, the only thing you are judged on in the end of these purple victory points, and there are not many ways to get them.

511
00:34:44,639 --> 00:34:48,480
Scott: The main way to get them is to discover new sciences.

512
00:34:48,761 --> 00:34:49,860
Scott: And what are new sciences?

513
00:34:49,880 --> 00:34:51,679
Scott: They're really just machines, right?

514
00:34:51,840 --> 00:34:53,179
Scott: There's a stack of cards.

515
00:34:53,380 --> 00:34:54,600
Rym: There's some weird mechanics around them.

516
00:34:54,739 --> 00:34:55,404
Rym: Like they're there.

517
00:34:55,947 --> 00:35:02,840
Rym: If I was going to design a game like this, I would probably get rid of that and let it just be the core machines and not this somewhat complicated.

518
00:35:03,141 --> 00:35:06,980
Scott: Anyway, the way the most points is to basically discover these science cards.

519
00:35:07,141 --> 00:35:07,363
Scott: Right.

520
00:35:07,403 --> 00:35:12,479
Scott: And when you discover a science, you get this new machine because you discovered some science and then you get to use it.

521
00:35:12,882 --> 00:35:16,560
Scott: And then the next turn, everyone else gets that machine, too.

522
00:35:17,343 --> 00:35:17,544
Scott: Right.

523
00:35:17,585 --> 00:35:22,740
Scott: So you get the exclusive right to use it for a turn and then everyone else gets to start using it to turn after.

524
00:35:22,880 --> 00:35:27,559
Scott: However, that might not seem like, well, why would I discover this science if everyone else gets to use it?

525
00:35:27,661 --> 00:35:28,859
Scott: Well, just one turn later.

526
00:35:29,162 --> 00:35:31,020
Scott: Well, using it for the one turn is beneficial.

527
00:35:31,481 --> 00:35:34,440
Scott: But being the discoverer, you got a shit ton of victory points.

528
00:35:34,640 --> 00:35:35,865
Rym: Now, what do we say?

529
00:35:35,885 --> 00:35:39,400
Rym: Shit, like five victory points is a big goddamn deal.

530
00:35:39,480 --> 00:35:40,364
Scott: You got a lot of points.

531
00:35:40,425 --> 00:35:45,600
Rym: if you discover you'll have turns where you have like 20 cubes in front of you churning around.

532
00:35:46,002 --> 00:35:50,705
Rym: And the output of all that nonsense is like two victory points and you're very happy with yourself.

533
00:35:50,785 --> 00:35:57,900
Scott: The other thing is that to discover these sciences, you need to have a lot of cubes that are very and are all the same kind.

534
00:35:58,001 --> 00:36:02,483
Scott: And that is hard to do because you crank all your machines and they spit out a pile of cubes.

535
00:36:02,845 --> 00:36:06,285
Scott: But those cubes are going to be all sorts of different funny colors all over the place.

536
00:36:06,326 --> 00:36:07,880
Rym: You know, there's making a lot of green cubes.

537
00:36:08,382 --> 00:36:10,299
Scott: I like to get at some of the sciences.

538
00:36:10,600 --> 00:36:12,619
Scott: It was like you need 12 blue cubes.

539
00:36:12,720 --> 00:36:15,655
Scott: And I'm like, oh, I got a 10 and no one's going to trade me any.

540
00:36:15,876 --> 00:36:17,749
Scott: like I was about to get someone to trade me one.

541
00:36:17,769 --> 00:36:19,040
Scott: And they're like, wait a minute.

542
00:36:19,902 --> 00:36:22,927
Scott: And they didn't trade me because they saw that I would basically win the game if they did that.

543
00:36:22,988 --> 00:36:23,499
Scott: And they were right.

544
00:36:23,660 --> 00:36:23,881
Rym: Yep.

545
00:36:23,922 --> 00:36:29,420
Rym: So that's the the only real problem I have with this game, because, again, the naive aspect doesn't really bother me.

546
00:36:29,480 --> 00:36:32,579
Rym: That's just sort of fascinating, but because the game was good.

547
00:36:33,141 --> 00:36:45,280
Rym: But when we played it, the machine management itself, the solo game of manage my machine, even if there was no trading, is actually pretty complex and interesting in its own right.

548
00:36:45,400 --> 00:36:46,003
Scott: There are also.

549
00:36:46,023 --> 00:36:50,579
Scott: the one interesting thing is that some machines, including your starting ones, could be upgraded.

550
00:36:51,664 --> 00:36:51,848
Scott: Right.

551
00:36:51,868 --> 00:36:52,380
Scott: So, oh, yeah.

552
00:36:52,540 --> 00:36:55,280
Scott: That mechanic you try to get you can get victory points for doing that, too.

553
00:36:55,320 --> 00:36:59,520
Rym: It's like I don't like burn a science and upgrade in order to in order to upgrade mine.

554
00:36:59,620 --> 00:37:04,740
Scott: I needed forest planets to like devour and I was trying to get people to trade me forest.

555
00:37:05,081 --> 00:37:06,799
Rym: And I had a ton of them, but you wouldn't give me enough cubes.

556
00:37:07,280 --> 00:37:08,438
Scott: I could didn't have enough cubes.

557
00:37:08,540 --> 00:37:11,420
Rym: Well, that was going to give you my forest planet that gave me free green cubes.

558
00:37:12,040 --> 00:37:12,221
Scott: Yeah.

559
00:37:12,723 --> 00:37:21,062
Scott: But, you know, you see the idea here and this the board, my starting suggestion seemed to imply that people would totally trade me those and they totally wouldn't know the science.

560
00:37:21,102 --> 00:37:33,940
Rym: upgrade pads are sort of interesting in that they they give you another route to sort of optimize and build your own world and adjust to the semi randomness that might be coming at you from other players.

561
00:37:34,040 --> 00:37:44,819
Scott: The other thing is that when you start discovering lots of sciences or other players discover lots of sciences, some of those machines, the sciences can be upgraded by discarding other ones.

562
00:37:44,961 --> 00:37:47,779
Scott: So it's like it's like I'll give up this machine I never use.

