00:37:48,202 --> 00:37:50,640
Scott: And that allows me to flip over this machine and make it better.

564
00:37:50,962 --> 00:37:54,240
Rym: I upgraded all of my starting machines because I had these weird like double machines.

565
00:37:54,520 --> 00:38:00,160
Scott: I wanted to because I gave a ton of victory points, but I was only able to do like two out of four, I think, because people wouldn't trade me there.

566
00:38:00,400 --> 00:38:05,560
Rym: I upgraded mine because it basically like I started spitting out more medium cubes, which is free medium cubes all over the place.

567
00:38:05,901 --> 00:38:06,864
Rym: Yeah.

568
00:38:07,205 --> 00:38:20,024
Scott: My ability was that if I got a planet from the board, not from trading, but if I bought one in the auction, then basically I it would be a double planet and spit out double the cubes.

569
00:38:20,125 --> 00:38:24,439
Scott: And that was crazy, ridiculously powerful, which is why I was trying to win a planet every single turn.

570
00:38:24,701 --> 00:38:24,982
Rym: Yeah.

571
00:38:25,303 --> 00:38:29,762
Scott: However, my ships were like half power or something because I was the plant people.

572
00:38:30,103 --> 00:38:33,679
Scott: So I had to get tons of ships and trades with people and then spend them all.

573
00:38:33,981 --> 00:38:39,105
Rym: See, the machine I kept cranking that it told me crank, it gave me a ton of ships every time I cranked it.

574
00:38:39,507 --> 00:38:43,599
Rym: So I always had a bunch of ships and pretty much get whatever I wanted anyway.

575
00:38:43,981 --> 00:38:48,119
Rym: So the other really interesting thing is, remember, we said that the game gives very specific advice to the players.

576
00:38:49,040 --> 00:38:51,640
Rym: The game gives up.

577
00:38:51,860 --> 00:38:57,120
Rym: I've never seen a game give this detail of helpful directional heuristics.

578
00:38:57,160 --> 00:38:58,479
Scott: It was like a strategy guide.

579
00:38:58,861 --> 00:39:02,020
Rym: So on every machine, there'll be a ratio.

580
00:39:02,301 --> 00:39:12,759
Rym: It'll be like three to four or three to five or one to two or three and a half to four or three and three quarters to four.

581
00:39:13,501 --> 00:39:22,497
Rym: The game basically assigns an arbitrary value to everything that can be in the game, like every kind of cube and any machine.

582
00:39:23,725 --> 00:39:25,080
Rym: It'll give you this number.

