00:40:09,811 --> 00:40:15,039
Scott: if you pay attention to that, you shouldn't be able to get ripped off because you know what values of things are instead of having to just guess.

595
00:40:15,321 --> 00:40:28,479
Scott: Yeah, like I see a lot of people that's good, I think, because first of all, I think you've got to avoid being trapped by that because there's times where it's like, well, I need to make this uneven trade because actually it pays out bigger for me because I can activate one more machine.

596
00:40:29,161 --> 00:40:36,499
Scott: But also a lot of people who play games with open trading have no idea how to value things at all when there's just free valuing.

597
00:40:36,761 --> 00:40:40,561
Rym: Now, if it's a relatively simple game, figuring that out is one of the skills of the game.

598
00:40:40,601 --> 00:40:44,080
Rym: I feel like if I had to figure that out, I just wouldn't trade it with anyone.

599
00:40:44,382 --> 00:40:45,939
Rym: Maybe this game's got so much going on.

600
00:40:46,080 --> 00:40:51,239
Scott: Yeah, but it's like, you know, people who play games with just like where they have to value things on their own.

601
00:40:51,803 --> 00:40:53,259
Scott: A lot of people have trouble with that.

602
00:40:53,601 --> 00:41:00,120
Scott: So telling people what a fair trade is protects them from sharky good players trying to rip them off.

603
00:41:00,341 --> 00:41:11,780
Rym: I think that the majority of games of modern art I've ever played have had at least one player bid more money for a painting than it could possibly be worth in the best possible circumstances.

604
00:41:12,380 --> 00:41:16,640
Rym: There is literally I can think of almost no reason you should ever do that.

605
00:41:16,940 --> 00:41:23,900
Scott: It's like that painting, no matter what the draw is, if you get the perfect draw for the rest of the game, that painting will be worth 50.

606
00:41:23,900 --> 00:41:25,300
Scott: Why are you bidding 60?

607
00:41:25,300 --> 00:41:26,699
Scott: You're just losing ten dollars.

608
00:41:27,203 --> 00:41:27,978
Scott: Why would you do this?

609
00:41:28,341 --> 00:41:31,680
Rym: You're giving me an extra ten dollars for nothing.

610
00:41:31,884 --> 00:41:32,598
Rym: Are you sure?

611
00:41:33,242 --> 00:41:33,968
Rym: And they're always sure.

612
00:41:34,049 --> 00:41:35,260
Rym: They always think they got a good plan.

613
00:41:35,421 --> 00:41:37,008
Rym: I never understood why I don't.

614
00:41:37,129 --> 00:41:49,960
Rym: I don't get it, but I've never seen a game give this granular level of like base pricing or base heuristics embedded into the game and coupled with the player advice, which again is shockingly specific.

615
00:41:50,704 --> 00:41:51,618
Rym: I just don't know.

616
00:41:52,883 --> 00:41:54,960
Rym: I don't know how I feel about that in the long run.

617
00:41:55,080 --> 00:41:56,999
Rym: I don't know if it's a good idea or a bad idea.

618
00:41:57,540 --> 00:42:06,966
Rym: I don't know if it's a sign that maybe the game needs to be more elegant or if it's a way to take a messy game and make it playable with a smaller number of learning games.

619
00:42:07,329 --> 00:42:08,377
Rym: It's a complicated situation.

620
00:42:09,060 --> 00:42:24,220
Scott: All I can say is that the name of this game and the graphic design of this game and the heritage of this game make it seem like a scary, scary, complicated for X space game when in reality it's just a game where you trade cubes, put them in a machine to get more cubes as efficiently as possible to get more cubes.

621
00:42:24,560 --> 00:42:27,179
Scott: And hopefully you have the most victory cubes at the end of the game.

622
00:42:27,962 --> 00:42:30,300
Scott: And it's a really straightforward kind of game.

623
00:42:30,340 --> 00:42:39,146
Scott: If you like trading with people and bargaining, then this is the game for you, especially if you like wooden cubes and an outer space theme and asymmetry, a little bit of asymmetry.

624
00:42:39,529 --> 00:42:41,160
Scott: This game could be way fun for you.

625
00:42:41,261 --> 00:42:42,559
Scott: It's like, hey, it's not bad.

626
00:42:43,061 --> 00:42:50,838
Scott: But I think if they fix the graphic design and maybe reduced some of the text on the cards, it would actually be much more approachable.

627
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:53,326
Scott: So don't be you got to.

628
00:42:53,788 --> 00:43:05,001
Rym: you know, if you're really in the mood for trading trades of Genoa or this, it's hard to say, though, because at the same time, a lot of the clutter on the cards is things like showing you what's on the back of a card that could be flipped.

629
00:43:05,162 --> 00:43:05,423
Scott: Yep.

630
00:43:05,945 --> 00:43:12,920
Rym: Or that heuristic, which I feel like without the heuristic, it would take a couple of plays before you could actually play the game.

631
00:43:14,324 --> 00:43:14,585
Rym: Yep.

632
00:43:14,605 --> 00:43:27,359
Rym: So the other real problem is that if the game is primarily about trading among our group, which was all like super savvy, sharp players, no one was willing to trade unless they were fucking ripping someone off in most cases, which is how we do.

633
00:43:28,141 --> 00:43:30,020
Rym: So there wasn't that much trading.

634
00:43:30,140 --> 00:43:30,240
Rym: Right.

635
00:43:30,301 --> 00:43:36,559
Rym: I would I would always like almost always, if I couldn't get a good trade, I'd just say fuck it and work on my machine.

636
00:43:37,461 --> 00:43:44,400
Rym: And Matt gave some good feedback that by the time he had optimized his machine and knew what he wanted to do to trade, everyone else was done trading.

637
00:43:44,540 --> 00:43:45,262
Rym: It didn't care anymore.

638
00:43:45,383 --> 00:43:52,920
Rym: I just know that I feel like it's more that the machine and the trading are both equal cognitive loads.

639
00:43:54,221 --> 00:44:02,722
Rym: And unless everyone in the group sets the balance between the two in terms of how they spend their term at around the same place, either some people are never going to get to trade.

640
00:44:02,742 --> 00:44:08,389
Scott: I think his cognitive load was bigger because his cubes were wild, whereas I drew mine was just like, oh, I have.

641
00:44:08,670 --> 00:44:14,220
Scott: I went basically went down each machine in order of efficiency and power and was like, can I power this one?

642
00:44:14,502 --> 00:44:15,999
Scott: Yes, I have the cubes for that assigned.

643
00:44:16,460 --> 00:44:23,080
Scott: I just went down until, well, I can't possibly power any more machines and I can't possibly get more efficiency out of the machines.

644
00:44:23,441 --> 00:44:27,240
Scott: Let's look at the what I have left and try to trade it to get ships and whatever I need.

645
00:44:27,380 --> 00:44:27,763
Rym: See, I would.

646
00:44:27,883 --> 00:44:31,717
Rym: I would look from the perspective of here are things I want to do and here are things I like to do.

647
00:44:32,241 --> 00:44:36,385
Rym: And I would make a short note in my head of the kinds of cubes I need to do the things I'd like to do.

648
00:44:36,405 --> 00:44:38,560
Rym: And I wouldn't actively try to trade with people.

649
00:44:38,966 --> 00:44:39,639
Rym: I would listen.

650
00:44:40,081 --> 00:44:46,300
Rym: And if I heard anyone say the type of cube that I needed for the thing I'd like to do, I would look up and try to make a deal.

651
00:44:46,360 --> 00:44:48,199
Rym: But otherwise, I ignored what everyone else was doing.

652
00:44:49,100 --> 00:44:54,300
Rym: And then I had a second bucket of things I had to do and I can't do with my machine.

653
00:44:54,901 --> 00:44:58,840
Rym: And that was the only time I would actually go up and say, anyone got any green cubes?

654
00:44:59,802 --> 00:45:03,600
Rym: I need green cubes, anyone, any Bueller, anyone.

655
00:45:04,600 --> 00:45:05,042
Rym: But I do.

656
00:45:05,122 --> 00:45:15,899
Rym: I do feel like a problem is if I were trying to play this game more seriously, there's another thing I'd have to take into account, which is the thing you take into account in every other game that allows trading.

657
00:45:17,144 --> 00:45:18,620
Rym: How close is Scott to winning?

658
00:45:18,960 --> 00:45:19,101
Rym: Yeah.

659
00:45:19,382 --> 00:45:20,206
Rym: How many points does?

660
00:45:20,267 --> 00:45:22,800
Scott: it is very difficult to track the positional heuristic.

661
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:29,546
Scott: I wanted to sort of spread my trades evenly in the game so that way I wouldn't benefit anyone else more.

662
00:45:29,586 --> 00:45:35,200
Scott: Because when you trade with someone and it's you're not getting ripped off, you're basically boosting the two of you ahead of all the other players.

663
00:45:35,641 --> 00:45:41,100
Scott: So if I trade with everyone evenly, I'm boosting myself, boost, boost four times because four other players, but that's not enough.

664
00:45:41,240 --> 00:45:41,723
Rym: You got to pay attention.

665
00:45:41,743 --> 00:45:42,728
Scott: They're getting boosted once.

666
00:45:42,808 --> 00:45:50,779
Rym: each is Rym trading with Chris a lot, because if that's true, you don't want to trade with Chris at all, probably, because then if you spread evenly, Chris is still plus one.

667
00:45:50,940 --> 00:45:53,431
Rym: Yeah, but there's almost there's.

668
00:45:53,451 --> 00:45:55,762
Rym: I don't think there's any way for a human to keep track of that.

669
00:45:55,802 --> 00:45:58,780
Scott: I could not keep track of who had what points really at all.

670
00:45:58,900 --> 00:45:59,644
Scott: It was too hard.

671
00:45:59,926 --> 00:46:00,810
Scott: And plus you keep.

672
00:46:00,830 --> 00:46:03,333
Scott: you get these victory point chips and keep them secret behind a shield.

673
00:46:03,557 --> 00:46:03,659
Scott: Yep.

674
00:46:04,160 --> 00:46:11,181
Rym: So so what I wonder is the people who are deeply into this game and really focus on the trading.

675
00:46:12,023 --> 00:46:19,205
Rym: I wonder if they just trade more without considering the true ramifications of their trading.

676
00:46:19,225 --> 00:46:20,639
Scott: The victory points are behind a shield, too.

677
00:46:20,740 --> 00:46:21,964
Rym: Yeah.

678
00:46:21,984 --> 00:46:36,359
Rym: Or are they perhaps the kinds of people who might be drawn to this kind of game or graphic design, the kinds of people who will let the game take six hours to ensure that they fully explore the trading and the machining on every turn?

679
00:46:37,320 --> 00:46:43,880
Rym: Because this feels like the kind of game to where there are people who will play it for six hours and enjoy every minute of those six hours.

680
00:46:44,040 --> 00:46:45,138
Scott: We played it much faster than that.

681
00:46:46,061 --> 00:46:51,228
Scott: I could be if we played it again, knowing the rules now, we could play it much, much faster than it looks like.

682
00:46:51,269 --> 00:46:52,640
Scott: It looks like a game that will take six hours.

683
00:46:52,741 --> 00:46:54,899
Scott: We could play it in like one hour and maybe a little more.

684
00:46:55,161 --> 00:46:56,066
Rym: I think hour and a half.

685
00:46:56,086 --> 00:46:58,922
Rym: We could crank this game out if everyone already knew how to play.

686
00:46:59,023 --> 00:47:01,680
Scott: And I didn't have to remember anything and such and such.

687
00:47:01,880 --> 00:47:08,760
Rym: And everyone is willing to not try to track a true positional heuristic of all the other players because I don't think it's possible.

688
00:47:09,980 --> 00:47:12,600
Rym: I wonder if you could make the trading more interesting.

689
00:47:12,921 --> 00:47:17,564
Rym: You couldn't really fully structure it because that'd be a very different game and it would probably take a lot longer.

690
00:47:18,126 --> 00:47:36,362
Rym: But if there were some way to implicitly advertise trades, like if you had a set of boards, you could like just put in front of you, that's like, I want to trade this because I know if I could have looked up and seen advertised trades, that might have sped up my own turn instead of everyone yelling at each other all the time.

691
00:47:36,402 --> 00:47:36,603
Rym: But the

692
00:47:36,664 --> 00:47:50,800
Scott: one thing this game actually got me thinking about was not not you know, it's not something I think this game should do, but maybe for a different game is, you know, we just talked about the knowing who you're trading with because you don't want to boost the person who's in first along with yourself.

693
00:47:50,840 --> 00:47:52,206
Scott: You want to trade with people below you.

694
00:47:52,287 --> 00:47:52,508
Scott: Right.

695
00:47:53,352 --> 00:47:58,072
Scott: Or even with you to boost up and catch up to the people who are ahead of you if you're not in first already.

696
00:47:58,313 --> 00:47:58,775
Scott: Yeah.

697
00:47:59,116 --> 00:48:03,733
Scott: Is a game where somehow you could trade but not know who you're trading with.

698
00:48:04,074 --> 00:48:10,904
Scott: You just see deals and you can make them or not make them based on their own merits, not knowing who's on the other end.

699
00:48:11,085 --> 00:48:12,653
Scott: And that, you know, just some kind of game.

700
00:48:12,774 --> 00:48:15,589
Scott: I'm sure there might be a game like that, but, you know, I've never played it.

701
00:48:15,971 --> 00:48:17,761
Scott: It would be cool if there was a game like that.

702
00:48:17,821 --> 00:48:23,586
Scott: Perhaps it could use some sort of market as a middleman to obfuscate the who you're trading with or something.

703
00:48:23,606 --> 00:48:39,053
Scott: Uh, and thus, you know, you wouldn't have this sort of like politics that would go in a game like that, but you still have all the fun of trading and making deals because you'd be like, all right, I'll trade three blue cubes for two greens and and it's no one knows it's you.

704
00:48:39,395 --> 00:48:50,782
Rym: And so anyone who's willing to trade two greens for three blues is look and sees that and it's like, but that does remove what a lot of people like about these kinds of free form trading games, which is the politics side.

705
00:48:50,843 --> 00:48:51,867
Rym: Yeah, the negotiation.

706
00:48:52,249 --> 00:48:53,695
Scott: Well, I think here's the thing.

707
00:48:53,736 --> 00:48:57,728
Scott: I think if you did this, you could somehow keep the negotiation right.

708
00:48:58,069 --> 00:49:07,183
Scott: But by making the recipient of the person offering the trade anonymous, I think you actually flip the negotiation to the other side, right?

709
00:49:07,223 --> 00:49:12,767
Scott: If I go to you in a game Rym and I say, hey, Rym, I see you got two greens, I'll trade you one blue for it.

710
00:49:12,807 --> 00:49:13,370
Scott: What do you do?

711
00:49:13,591 --> 00:49:14,816
Scott: You go, give me two blue.

712
00:49:14,837 --> 00:49:17,790
Scott: Yeah, because I'm the one asking and I'm asking you.

713
00:49:17,810 --> 00:49:20,562
Rym: Well, you kept saying, hey, anyone got any forest colonies?

714
00:49:20,582 --> 00:49:21,446
Rym: I'm like, fuck you.

715
00:49:21,627 --> 00:49:21,968
Rym: Exactly.

716
00:49:21,988 --> 00:49:23,877
Rym: As I look at my five forest college.

717
00:49:23,938 --> 00:49:24,420
Rym: Exactly.

718
00:49:24,580 --> 00:49:28,638
Scott: But now let's say let's make it suddenly anonymous with this market aspect, right?

719
00:49:28,659 --> 00:49:38,255
Scott: Where there's some sort of intermediary and all you see out is out on the board, the opportunity to trade those two greens for a blue and maybe someone else sees it, too.

720
00:49:38,676 --> 00:49:40,643
Scott: So suddenly no longer is it.

721
00:49:40,944 --> 00:49:43,655
Scott: I'm going to give Scott as little as I can for that blue I need.

722
00:49:43,756 --> 00:49:48,520
Scott: It's now I need to get that blue because someone else is going to take that deal off the board.

723
00:49:48,962 --> 00:49:54,287
Scott: And now you're suddenly putting three greens or four greens because someone else is going to put in three greens, right?

724
00:49:54,528 --> 00:50:05,986
Scott: So you just by taking away knowing who the recipient is, you can suddenly it's now more of an eBay situation and less of a give Scott as little as possible situation.

725
00:50:06,027 --> 00:50:06,469
Rym: That'd be easy.

726
00:50:06,569 --> 00:50:09,141
Rym: A video game that is very difficult to do in a physical game.

727
00:50:09,221 --> 00:50:10,766
Scott: Oh, yes, yes, yes, obviously.

728
00:50:11,047 --> 00:50:17,915
Rym: But that's why I wonder if some sort of player aid, like not a rule, like I don't want to add structure to this.

729
00:50:17,955 --> 00:50:19,623
Rym: I don't want it to be like Res Publica.

730
00:50:19,643 --> 00:50:22,953
Rym: We're like, I have two blue cubes.

731
00:50:23,294 --> 00:50:23,795
Scott: Yeah, no.

732
00:50:23,915 --> 00:50:24,738
Scott: Oh, Res Publica.

733
00:50:24,778 --> 00:50:25,199
Scott: That's right.

734
00:50:25,219 --> 00:50:27,385
Rym: I don't want that.

735
00:50:27,626 --> 00:50:29,512
Scott: Yeah, that was interesting, though.

736
00:50:29,552 --> 00:50:30,194
Scott: But yeah, not that.

737
00:50:30,395 --> 00:50:30,615
Rym: Yeah.

738
00:50:30,876 --> 00:50:53,644
Rym: But I really wonder if you put some soft mechanic where they were player aids like a pool of cards or cardboard things where you could basically advertise trades without having to keep yelling at everyone like you have a common area in the middle and I can just put like three advertised trades like I'm willing to trade blue cubes and I like here's three blue cubes and willing to trade.

739
00:50:53,664 --> 00:50:58,585
Scott: There is some physical mechanism for creating a trade advertisement and then you could shuffle them.

740
00:50:58,887 --> 00:50:59,871
Rym: Yeah, right.

741
00:50:59,911 --> 00:51:03,351
Scott: And then you've splay them out and you know which ones are yours because you made them.

742
00:51:03,612 --> 00:51:04,478
Rym: Oh, I don't even want to shove.

743
00:51:04,498 --> 00:51:07,775
Rym: I don't even care about the anonymous part because even better, you know what?

744
00:51:08,017 --> 00:51:10,107
Scott: Maybe some of them are yours and you know what?

745
00:51:10,147 --> 00:51:12,438
Scott: You shuffle them up and you splay them out, right?

746
00:51:12,458 --> 00:51:17,376
Scott: You accidentally trade yourself because I put down trade one blue for two green, right?

747
00:51:17,497 --> 00:51:17,758
Scott: Yeah.

748
00:51:17,818 --> 00:51:19,605
Scott: Maybe I want to turn a blue into two green.

749
00:51:19,686 --> 00:51:21,112
Scott: So I put it out there and then I use it.

750
00:51:22,318 --> 00:51:25,469
Scott: I make the deal with myself, but I guess, oh, but those are my two green.

751
00:51:25,790 --> 00:51:26,953
Scott: Yeah.

752
00:51:27,034 --> 00:51:27,435
Scott: Nevermind.

753
00:51:28,358 --> 00:51:30,304
Rym: It's like buying your own stock through scotch ride.

754
00:51:30,324 --> 00:51:31,226
Rym: Like you're just paying $14 son.

755
00:51:31,266 --> 00:51:42,748
Rym: So, but indeed because it is impossible to keep a reasonable positional heuristic in this game on all the other players and you have to just sort of ignore that aspect.

756
00:51:43,371 --> 00:51:49,617
Rym: I feel like you can avoid the politics situation by just letting it wash over you and focusing on making good machine.

757
00:51:49,698 --> 00:51:51,727
Rym: That's what I did and focusing on good trades.

758
00:51:51,767 --> 00:51:52,289
Rym: That's what I did.

759
00:51:52,310 --> 00:52:03,795
Rym: But then to keep the spirit of the game instead of doing some structural change like you're talking about, just having physical implements to be able to advertise trades without having to yell constantly.

760
00:52:04,698 --> 00:52:07,347
Rym: That would make this game cleaner to play.

761
00:52:07,728 --> 00:52:15,476
Rym: The only problem with that is that there is no table on earth that will have enough free space for said trade advertisement pieces.

762
00:52:15,878 --> 00:52:17,244
Scott: This game has got a lot of stuff.

763
00:52:17,305 --> 00:52:18,330
Scott: It takes up a lot of room.

764
00:52:18,350 --> 00:52:19,335
Scott: You need a big table.

765
00:52:19,435 --> 00:52:21,485
Scott: There's going to be cubes everywhere.

766
00:52:21,545 --> 00:52:33,990
Rym: We were playing games on a table that was big enough for us, our group to play two separate giant games and yet a small game of sidereal nonsense literally covered every square inch of the table.

767
00:52:34,572 --> 00:52:38,146
Scott: Granted it was two, three player games and this was one five player game.

768
00:52:38,427 --> 00:52:43,866
Rym: I do not own or know of a game that I would be willing to play that takes up more table space than this game.

769
00:52:43,886 --> 00:52:47,520
Scott: I think Eclipse takes up more space than this.

770
00:52:48,844 --> 00:52:52,074
Rym: I think Eclipse might not actually take up more space than this.

771
00:52:52,094 --> 00:52:52,636
Scott: I think it does.

772
00:52:53,439 --> 00:52:53,860
Scott: Definitely.

773
00:52:54,601 --> 00:52:56,028
Rym: Maybe with the science area.

774
00:52:56,049 --> 00:52:58,059
Scott: Yeah, Eclipse definitely takes up more than this.

775
00:52:58,099 --> 00:53:04,194
Rym: Of course I remember the way we got around that is we put the science area on the other side of the room just like on it so you could walk on a second table.

776
00:53:04,214 --> 00:53:08,318
Scott: because Eclipse is so big this game doesn't need a second table, but this game, it's just all your shit.

777
00:53:08,358 --> 00:53:11,587
Rym: Like your, your splay will be all over the place.

778
00:53:11,627 --> 00:53:12,509
Scott: Yes, it was big.

779
00:53:14,053 --> 00:53:24,220
Rym: Uh, but yeah, I enjoyed this game despite not expecting to based on my initial impression, looking at the rules or the graphics.

780
00:53:24,360 --> 00:53:24,561
Rym: Yup.

781
00:53:24,702 --> 00:53:25,425
Rym: I would play it again.

782
00:53:25,445 --> 00:53:31,529
Scott: The art, the art that is there that is like not the graphic design, but the art, the drawings is way good.

783
00:53:31,749 --> 00:53:35,923
Rym: Also the art of the proper nouns as in the world.

784
00:53:35,943 --> 00:53:38,977
Rym: Uh, I'm not the kind of person who cares about that sort of thing.

